{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493359"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:07:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1300"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1300"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.74,0.08,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94265"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1300"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77330"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3340"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"6361"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"571"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42279"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents by ambulance to the Emergency Department from a music festival with confusion and a deep cut on her thigh. She has a history of recurrent drug-induced psychosis and was commenced on aripiprazole by her psychiatrist one week ago. Her friend reports that she has been adherent with the medication and is unsure if she took any drugs at the festival, but knows that some of their friends had been using substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears diaphoretic, confused, and irritable. The cut on her leg is 15 cm long and appears to be a few hours old. There is fat on view and the edges do not oppose, with some erythema around the borders, but no exudate. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 160/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. She has marked muscle rigidity and decreased reflexes in her upper and lower limbs. Both pupils are equal and reactive to light. A repeat blood pressure 10 minutes later shows 120/50 mmHg. Blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 11.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein 15 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatine kinase 1500 U/L (26-192)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Methamphetamine toxicity","Gamma-hydroxybutyrate overdose","Malignant hyperthermia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eneuroleptic malignant syndrome (NMS)\u003C/strong\u003E. NMS is a life-threatening neurological emergency associated with antipsychotic medication, characterised by muscle rigidity, autonomic dysfunction, altered mental status, and fever. The onset of symptoms typically occurs within the first two weeks of starting or changing the dose of an antipsychotic medication, which aligns with this patient\u0027s recent initiation of aripiprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E shares some features with NMS but typically presents with hyperreflexia, myoclonus, and dilated pupils, which are not seen in this case. Additionally, serotonin syndrome is associated with serotonergic medications rather than antipsychotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethamphetamine toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E can present with hyperthermia, agitation, and autonomic instability. However, it typically causes hyperreflexia rather than the decreased reflexes seen here, and the muscle rigidity would be unusual. The temporal relationship with starting aripiprazole is more suggestive of NMS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-hydroxybutyrate overdose\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a decreased level of consciousness, bradycardia, and hypothermia rather than the hyperthermia and muscle rigidity seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant hyperthermia\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited disorder triggered by certain anaesthetic agents, causing rapid onset of high fever and severe muscle rigidity. It typically occurs during or shortly after surgery and is not associated with antipsychotic medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key features supporting the diagnosis of NMS in this case are: 1. Recent initiation of an antipsychotic (aripiprazole) 2. Fever 3. Muscle rigidity 4. Autonomic instability (fluctuating blood pressure) 5. Altered mental status 6. Elevated creatine kinase (indicating muscle breakdown). Management of NMS involves immediate discontinuation of the offending antipsychotic, supportive care, and potentially specific treatments such as dantrolene or bromocriptine. This condition requires prompt recognition and treatment to prevent potentially fatal complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome is a neurological emergency associated with antipsychotic medication, characterised by muscle rigidity, autonomic dysfunction, altered mental status, and fever.","Distinguishing between neuroleptic malignant syndrome, serotonin syndrome, sepsis, and drug toxicity is crucial for appropriate management in psychiatric emergencies."],"references":["Larach MG, Gronert GA, Allen GC, et al. Clinical presentation, treatment, and complications of malignant hyperthermia in North America from 1987 to 2006. Anesth Analg 2010; 110:498. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20081135/","Whelton, PK, Carey, RM et al. 2017 American Heart Association (AHA) Guideline for the Prevention, Detection, Evaluation, and Management of High Blood Pressure in Adults. Hypertension. 2017;71(6):13\u2013e115. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/HYP.0000000000000065","Levenson JL. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome. Am J Psychiatry 1985;142:1137. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2863986/","Adnet P, Lestavel P, Krivosic-Horber R. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome. Br J Anaesth 2000;85:129. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10928001/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77330"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1300"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77330"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T17:16:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T17:18:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1300"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94265"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","l